Update with the inspiration from the fellow forecasters: 
@IcemanPolitics offers a baseline of 18 % as 9 out of 40 years had an arms agreement between USA and Soviet Union/Russia (9:40 odds for nuclear treaties). 
@mbayer123 offers a baserate of 14 % looking at withdrawals from international agreements in of Trump administration and how many times the negotiations were taking place.  Both forecasters offer an interesting, but quite different approach to the asses the starting point in the outside view. It would be wise to use both insights and take an average (even through are pretty close right now). But first I will try to get around, some methodological traps.  Looking at historical data to find out, how many times USA and Soviet Union/Russia to get a feeling how common are the agreements. But the world order has changed. Most of the arms agreements listed in https://www.armscontrol.org/print/2556 are made under the bipolar world order (until the end of the Cold War) and during the total dominance of the USA - uni-polar world order. I would argue that the rise of BRICS countries, especially economic rise of China and Russia's aggressive behavior is a challenge to the hegemonic world order of the United States. That is why I suggest to shorten the time line to around 2000, even if its not given that we live in a multipolar world order, but I believe, as mentioned before rise of China and Russia has created different dynamics in the international system. That leaves us only with 2 agreements. SORT (2002) and New Start (2010) in 19 years. 2/19 = 10,5 %.  It would be efficient to look at not only how many international agreement Trump administration has pulled USA out, but also how many Trump has signed. Looking only on withdrawals creates a negative bias. However, after searching the internet for a database of international treaties, I give up. There are no good search engine which is up to date. If anybody knows a database – I would appreciate the tip. Anyhow, I will go with @mbayer123 ‘s baserate of 14 %. The average of the two baselines is 12,25 % chance that the negotiations on arms control would begin this year.  As the date is 1 october it takes three month of a year, so lets say the baserate should go down by 25 % of 12,25 = 9 ,19 % is my base rate. So lets look on the inside view. I will stick with my augmentation in my earlier forecast: 
It seems that Trumps idea of strengthening the economy also involves boosting the military production. The arms control only limits that cause. 
In my opinion, hard line against European NATO allies for reaching 2% of GDP spending on military is also a part of Trumps strategy. 
On the other side, Russia’s economy is collapsing, but Putin needs a way to show the domestic crowd Russian international strength - focusing on military and framing that Russia will not be controlled by the US, is a great distraction from domestic problems. Domestic politics in both countries do not favor a new agreement soon. That must cut the base rate twice, one time per partner that need to be willing to negotiate. So 9,19 % / 2 = 4,56 % for USA. And once again for Russia. 4,56 % / 2 = 2,28 % is the final forecast.
